  "prompt": "How can you determine the derivative of [math]\\sin x^2[/math]?",
  "response": "To find the derivative of \\(\\sin(x^2)\\), we'll use the chain rule. The chain rule states that if you have a function in the form \\(f(g(x))\\), then its derivative is \\(f'(g(x)) \\cdot g'(x)\\).\n\nLet's break down \\(\\sin(x^2)\\):\n\n1. Let \\(f(u) = \\sin(u)\\) where \\(u = x^2\\).\n2. We need to find the derivative of \\(f(u)\\) with respect to \\(u\\), and the derivative of \\(u\\) with respect to \\(x\\).\n\nFirst, the derivative of \\(\\sin(u)\\) with respect to \\(u\\) is:\n\\[ f'(u) = \\cos(u) \\]\n\nNext, the derivative of \\(u = x^2\\) with respect to \\(x\\) is:\n\\[ g'(x) = 2x \\]\n\nNow, applying the chain rule:\n\\[ \\frac{d}{dx} \\sin(x^2) = f'(g(x)) \\cdot g'(x) \\]\n\\[ = \\cos(x^2) \\cdot 2x \\]\n\\[ = 2x \\cos(x^2) \\]\n\nSo, the derivative of \\(\\sin(x^2)\\) is:\n\\[ \\frac{d}{dx} \\sin(x^2) = 2x \\cos(x^2) \\]",
